        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe protoplanetary disks around HD 100546 and HD 100453.  Our goals are to explore the dust and gas structures in these systems.  To compare the results of the two targets, we request the same (or similar) observing setups.

To probe both the velocity and spatial structures of the disk, which is important when we probe the structures that might be of dynamical origin, we request 0.1 km/s velocity resolution in line observations.  This is approximately 1/10 of the Keplerian motion at 20 AU (cavity edge) and therefore should be comparable with the disk sound speed.  Dynamical processes in the disk, such as disk-planet interaction, often causes the perturbation of the gas velocity of the order of sound speed.  Therefore, we expect that we can at least marginally probe the signatures of such dynamical activities in the disk.  In the calculations of the parametrized disk models described in the sensitivity section of Technical Justification and in Scientific Justification, we have checked that the spatial resolution of 0.15 asec is enough to resolve the channel map images.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe protoplanetary disks around HD 100546 and HD 100453.  Our goals are to explore the dust and gas structures in these systems.  To compare the results of the two targets, we request the same (or similar) observing setups.

We aim to probe the structures close to the central star, which are seen in NIR imaging observations.  We choose 0.15 asec spatial resolution to resolve the inner cavity and to find out a hint of spiral structures observed in L'-band observations.  The radius of inner cavity (14 AU) corresponds to 0.14 asec.  With chosen spatial resolution of 0.15 asec, it is possible to resolve the inner cavity with several beams and measure the dust depletion within the cavity.  A possible gap structure in dust continuum emission hinted in Cycle 0 observations (Walsh et al. 2014) can be resolved with 0.15 asec resolution as well, 

To keep the observing time reasonable, we only use one telescope array configuration.  The largest angular scale should be within 1.9 asec to keep the number of telescope configuration one for HD 100546, according to OT.  Although HD 100546 disk extends to several 100 AU (several asec), the maximum angular scale of 1.9 asec is sufficient to achievse our science goal.  Many of interesting features revealed by NIR observations are within this range (Figure 1 of Scientific Justification).  Especially, the companion candidate HD 100546 b resides at the projected distance of 0.5 asec, which is within the range of the maximum recoverable scale.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe protoplanetary disks around HD 100546 and HD 100453.  Our goals are to explore the dust and gas structures in these systems.  To compare the results of the two targets, we request the same (or similar) observing setups.

We request the sensitivity of 2.5K for 12CO line.  This request is primarily determined by two scientific requirements.  One is to detect 12CO in HD 100453 system and the other is to detect 13CO in HD 100546 system.  Here, we present sensitivity calculations for HD 100546. (see Technical Justification of HD 100453 for the detection of 12CO in this system.)

For HD 100546, the detection of 12CO and marginal detection of 13CO have been already reported with APEX (Panic et al. 2010).  In ALMA Cycle 0, Walsh et al. (2014) spatially resolved the 12CO(3-2) emission with the peak flux density of 3100 mJy per 0.95 asec times 0.42 asec beam in the channel maps.  With the beam size of 0.15 asec, this results in 175 mJy per beam in our setup.  This means the signal-to-noise ratio of 32 for 12CO(3-2) emission.  With this signal-to-noise level, it is possible to detect the spatial variation of flux density at 10% level and therefore it is possible to discuss the small scale structures within the disk.

Panic et al. (2010) estimated that the H2 gas column density is 0.03 g/cm^2 based on the detection of 12CO(3-2) and the marginal detection of 13CO(3-2) with APEX.  This corresponds to the total gas mass of 0.1 MJ within 100 AU.

To investigate the observability of 13CO(3-2), we have done radiative transfer calculations (assuming LTE) with a simple parameterized disk model where surface density profile is proportional to r^{-1} (where r being the distance from the central star) and the temperature profile is proportional to r^{-0.5} with T=160 K at r=20 AU.  We vary the value of surface density at r=20AU.  If there is 0.1MJ of gas within 100AU, the typical brightness temperature of 13CO(3-2) emission at r=50AU is approximately 10K.  Therefore, we expect at least marginal detection of 13CO in a spatially resolved map with 0.1 km/s velocity resolution if sensitivity is set to 2.5K.  See Table 2 of Scientific Justification for details of the calculations.  In the case of low signal-to-noise ratio, we combine several channels in the post process to suppress the noise level.  The disk will still be both spatially and spectrally resolved, since our bandwidth of 0.1 km/s is sufficient for resolving the Keplerian motion (see Technical Justification of correlator configuration).

The continuum flux density of 37 mJy is estimated from Cycle 0 observations (0.5mJy rms and 1320 signal-to-noise per 0.95 asec times 0.42 asec beam; Walsh et al. 2014).  With the signal-to-noise ratio of more than 1100 in continuum emission, it is possible to measure the depth of the central cavity down to 1/300 level.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
