            <prj:justificationText>We observe protoplanetary disks around HD 100546 and HD 100453.  Our goals are to explore the dust and gas structures in these systems.  To compare the results of the two targets, we request the same (or similar) observing setups.

We aim to probe the small scale structures close to the central star.  Our Gemini/GPI observations have resolved the inner edge of the outer disk at 15-20 AU from the central star, which corresponds to approximately 0.15 asec.  Therefore, with 0.15 asec resolution, it is possible to resolve the inner cavity.

An important difference between HD 100453 and HD 100546 is the presence of binary companion.  We therefore propose to include the location of the binary within the recoverable scale.  According to OT, it is possible to set the largest angular scale of 2.5 asec without using additional 12 m array configuration.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe protoplanetary disks around HD 100546 and HD 100453.  Our goals are to explore the dust and gas structures in these systems.  To compare the results of the two targets, we request the same (or similar) observing setups.

We request the sensitivity of 2.5K for 12CO line.  This request is primarily determined by two scientific requirements.  One is to detect 12CO in HD 100453 system and the other is to detect 13CO in HD 100546 system.  Here, we present sensitivity calculations for HD 100453. (see Technical Justification of HD 100546 for the detection of 13CO.)

There is only upper limit in the amount gas in HD 100453 system and therefore, the primary goal for this object is to detect CO lines.  We discuss the detectable gas mass here.  To investigate the observability of 12CO(3-2), we have done radiative transfer calculations (assuming LTE) with a simple parameterized disk model where surface density profile is proportional to r^{-1} (where r being the distance from the central star) and the temperature profile is proportional to r^{-0.5} with T=160 K at r=20 AU.  We vary the value of surface density at r=20AU.  We have found that the lowest disk mass within 100AU where we can resolve both spatially and spectrally is of the order of 1/1000 of Jupiter mass (see Table 2 of Scientific Justification).  Since the dust mass in this system is estimated to be ~0.1 MJ, it is possible to detect and resolve CO lines even if the amount of gas is only 1% of dust mass.  By integrating spatially and/or by averaging over several velocity channels, we can increase the signal-to-noise ratio.  As stated in the Technical Justification of HD 100546 system, our bandwidth of 0.1 km/s sufficiently resolves the Keplerian motion.  Even in the case of non-detection, comparison between HD 100546 and HD 100453 systems gives us an insight into environmental effects on disk evolution.

For continuum observations, the total flux density of 265 mJy is obtained with SIMBA at 1.2mm wavelengths (Meeus et al. 2003).  With the flux slope of -2.8 (Meeus et al. 2003), the flux density at 345 GHz is 650 mJy.  If the disk is extended to 100 AU in radius, the expected flux per beam with 0.15 asec in size is approximately 5 mJy.  Note that this is a conservative estimate because it is likely that the disk is more compact due to the truncation by the binary companion.  In addition, our Gemini/GPI observations suggest that the polarized scattered light comes from only &lt;60-70 AU region from the central star.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
