    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe two evolved (~10Myr) protoplanetary disks showing spiral structures in recent NIR observations, HD 100546 and HD 100453, with 0.15 asec resolution in Band 7. HD 100546 is a single star with a large disk, having a directly imaged low-mass companion at ~50AU and another suspected one at ~10AU, just interior to the edge of the central cavity. Spiral-like features are found in recent Gemini/NICI L'-band observations. Reobservations from ALMA Cycle 0 (0.5 asec resolution) are warranted in order to resolve small scale structures. HD 100453 is a 1.05 asec separation binary with a circumprimary disk. Our recent Gemini/GPI observations found a conspicuous central cavity with two spiral arms.  Our NIR imaging observations are suggestive of the presence of forming planets in the disk midplane, but the strucrtures there can be probed only by high resolution mm-observations.

We aim to constrain the amount of gas and dust and find structural signatures of planet formation such as gaps and spirals. Comparison of the two systems with similar ages but very different environments gives us an insight into how the circumstellar environment affects the planet formation.
</prp:abstract>
